node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on August 23, 2021. May be an image of text that says '2021 HSA Contributions Contributions 2021 Total Contributions $2,123.07 as of 2021 INDIVIDUAL MAX FAMILY MAX $3,600 $7,200 CATCH-UP (AGE 55+) $1,000 @thatdebtfreelife'.

node.text:
HSA Update! 

I actually have contributed a total of $6,383.83 this calendar year to HSAs. 

A large portion of that ($3,440) went to maxing out my 2020 HSA earlier this year. 

The rest has been to my 2021 HSA. 

And, I actually have 2 HSAs. The one you see here which I started when I was with my previous employer—who didn’t offer an HSA. Plus one offered by my current employer. 

Haven’t decided a plan with respect to consolidating them or if I’ll continue to keep them both. I like the investment options in my personal HSA so much better than the one offered by my employer. But, when I contribute to my employer’s HSA, I can contribute pre-tax dollars. So that’s cool. But I do like the idea of having only one for ease/simplicity. 

Have you ever tried to consolidate HSAs?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on August 23, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '"Knowing something @THATDEBTFREELIFE doesn't change your life. Doing something does." -Marie Forleo'.

node.text:
You can read all the finance books and blogs in the world, scroll all the personal finance instas, listen to all the money podcasts, and nothing about your life will change until you start taking ACTION about the things you’re learning. Knowledge is fantastic—but it means absolutely nothing without the action to back it up. 

If you’ve been putting off taking that next step to get your finances in order, consider this your sign to pull the trigger. I suspect, deep down, you know what you should be doing and you just aren’t doing it. 

But if you’re clueless about where to start, check out my #onethingwednesday series where, every Wednesday, I share one simple actionable step you can take to bring yourself closer to financial healthiness. 

What’s one financial related task you’ve been dragging your feet on? Pull the trigger today!

node.text:
Here’s my 401(k) year to date progress. The employer match you see here includes matches I’ve received from both companies I worked for this year. 

I was contributing 15% to my 401(k) with my old employer. I’m not doing as much with my new employer since my salary is higher, and 15% would put me over the $19.5K limit. 

I won’t end up maxing it out for the year, but I’ll definitely hit over $19.5K total added to my 401(k) for the year when you include my employer contributions. And I’ll take that as a win.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on August 22, 2021. May be an image of money and text.

node.text:
Most of you know I switched jobs in March. With my new job, employees are eligible to participate in the 401(k) from day 1, so of course, ya girl signed up. 

I finally received my first ever matching contribution from my new employer, which (I think) are distributed quarterly. Hello, additional $1,000+ into my 401(k)! You’re looking good! 

In addition, my employer also recently announced a profit sharing bonus. Because the company is performing well, each employee received an additional $500 into his/her 401(k). 

I’ve never worked for a company that engages in profit sharing before (or truly values it’s employees like this company seems to!), so this was such a fun announcement to receive. 

How about you? Ever worked for a company that profit-shares? Also, if your employer provides a 401(k), do you know what the match is and are you participating? 

If you’re in debt, I’d encourage you to participate in your 401(k) still. At least contribute enough to get your full employer match.

May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'BREAKING NEWS Forbes Aug 20, 2021, 11:52am EDT 2,523 views Biden Administration Το Cancel Student Loan Interest Retroactively For 47,000 Military Service Members @thatdebtfreelife'.

node.text:
This relief is automatic. Qualifying service members do not have to apply for it. 

Who qualifies? Both current and former active duty service members deployed to areas that qualify them for imminent danger or hostile fire pay will have no interest accrue on certain federal student loans that were first disbursed on or after Oct. 1, 2008.

I linked a few articles in my stories for more info, which discusses this relief as well as Biden’s announcement to cancel $5.8 billion in student loans for 300,000 disabled borrowers.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on August 21, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Irvestuent Recap + $44K THIS YEAR $100K $80K $60K $20K $0 @thatdebtfreelife'.

node.text:
So far this year, the amount of money I have invested across all accounts has increased by $44K. 

To be clear, I haven’t invested that much, but that number represents the money I’ve put in plus growth.

I’m almost at my first $100K invested and can’t wait to hit that milestone! 

It may take a while since I’m pausing aggressive investing over the next several months to complete my new (to me) car fund, but it’ll happen soon enough! 

That big gap, btw, is when I did a rollover of my old 401(k) when I left my former employer. The money had to be sent via check to my IRA. Those few days where the money had been withdrawn from my 401(k) but not yet deposited in my IRA represents the dip you see on the graph. 

This graph is from the personal capital app, btw. An easy to use app that can be used to track investments and net worth. Do you track your investments and net worth?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on August 20, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'chHuse your mindset NOT THAT CHANGE YOUR FINANCIAL POSITION NO: Investing is just for rich people YES: Investing is how rich people get rich @THATDEBTFREELIFE'.

node.text:
I didn’t invest at all while I was paying off debt and strongly believed that it was the right way to go. I’ve since changed my mind, and I’d encourage you to continue (or start!) to invest even while in debt—at least enough to get your employer’s 401(k) match if you have one. 

I started aggressively investing in October of last year after I finished saving up a 6-month emergency fund. 

At the end of next month, I will have been investing aggressively for one year now, and can’t wait to share with you more details about it. 

Are you investing? If you know nothing about investing, my recommendation is to pick up JL Collins’ book, The Simple Path to Wealth and devour it.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Back to School traditions'.

node.text:
It’s the first day of school for us today, and I thought I’d share some of my back to school traditions with you. I share them every year, so if you’ve been around a while, you’ve heard these before. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We make pancakes in the shape of my son’s grade for the first day of school each year. We started with a K in kindergarten and this year we’ll be making “fifth grade pancakes.” Pancakes are his favorite breakfast, so this makes it extra special. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
My husband and I both go with him to class and walk him to his room on the first day. We couldn’t do it last year due to COVID, and I’m so glad we can this year. Since he’s a 5th grader, this will be the last year ever that I’ll get to walk him to his class on the first day of school. 😭😭😭#theygrowupsofast 
⁣⁣
Then I always take the day off, so I can be there at the bus stop to pick him up when he gets home from school. Since COVID, I’ve been mainly working from home, so no need to burn a vacation day and I can still be at the bus stop when he gets home. Yayyy!
⁣
Finally, I bake him freshly made chocolate chip cookies and serve them with milk for an after school snack. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We have done this every year (K, 1, 2, 3 and 4) and this will be our 6th year with these little traditions. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I love these traditions because they are simple and frugal, and my son looks forward to them each year. ⁣⁣You don’t have to spend a fortune to create lasting memories. Truth be told some of my most favorite childhood memories are the simple ones. 
⁣⁣
So what about you? When do your kids start school? Do you have any traditions for the start of a new school year? I’d love for you to share them below!
